## image coordinate system
The Python Imaging Library uses a Cartesian pixel coordinate system, with (0,0)
in the upper left corner. Note that the coordinates refer to the implied pixel
corners; the centre of a pixel addressed as (0, 0) actually lies at (0.5, 0.5).

Coordinates are usually passed to the library as 2-tuples (x, y). 
Rectangles are represented as 4-tuples, (x1, y1, x2, y2), with the upper left 
corner given first.

ValueError is raised if right coordinate is less than left or lower is less than upper


