the metod convert() flats the 3rd component of the image. tha its convert the e RGB figures into a one number that stans for gray scale.
"L" stands for Luminance — the perceived brightness of a pixel. It comes from color science terminology where luminance represents the light intensity component of an image, independent of color.
When you call .convert("L"), PIL transforms each RGB pixel into a single brightness value (0–255) using a weighted formula based on human perception:
L = 0.299 * R + 0.587 * G + 0.114 * B
Green gets the highest weight because our eyes are most sensitive to it, red next, blue least. This matches the ITU-R BT.601 standard for luminance.


IN the zoom_42 function The grayscale image is pasted onto an RGBA canvas. 
PIL converts the "L" mode image to RGBA during paste, resulting in pixels where
R == G == B == gray_value. 
When matplotlib receives a 4-channel RGBA image it uses the actual pixel
   values — all channels equal → gray. 

plt.imshow() receives a PIL Image in "L" mode directly (single channel / 2D). 
When matplotlib gets a 2D array with no colormap specified, it applies its 
default colormap — viridis — which maps low values to purple and high values
to yellow-green. Hence the greenish look.
This is a common matplotlib trap: 
grayscale arrays always need cmap='gray' explicitly, otherwise viridis is
  silently applied.
